<TEXT>
the air force found no 
problems in inspections wednesday of at least 19 b1b bombers 
which were grounded two days earlier after one of the planes swing 
wings punctured a fuel tank a spokesman said 
col larry greer of the strategic air command said six more of 
the older b1bs would be inspected before the air force decided 
whether to clear them for flight the inspections were to be 
completed at offut air force base by early thursday greer said 
sac has 97 b1bs which are up to 2 years old 
the 25 picked for inspection were representative of older b1bs 
at sacs four b1 wings greer said most are stationed at dyess 
air force base in texas mcconnell air force base in kansas grand 
forks air force base in north dakota and ellsworth air force base 
in south dakota 
other planes are stationed at a maintenance depot at tinker air 
force base in oklahoma and a contractors plant in palmdale calif 
the colonel said 
gen john t chain jr sacs commander will review inspection 
reports and make a final decision on whether the bombers should be 
returned to service greer said 
the fuel tank damaged during a routine preflight check at dyess 
was apparently punctured when the mechanism that sweeps the 
bombers wings back and forth malfunctioned pentagon spokesman dan 
howard said tuesday 
we are looking at something called the wingsweeper gear 
subassembly greer said wednesday thats the gear box inside 
the swing wings which gives it power to sweep the wings up and 
back you can sweep them back for a sort of delta shape to fly 
close to supersonic speeds and you sweep them out for landing and 
takeoff 
howard said the texas bombers crew was sweeping the wings 
forward and backward before taking off and discovered the wings 
were not moving evenly together 
