<TEXT>
consumers union reported wednesday 
that it found the controversial additive alar in nearly 
threefourths of the apple juice samples it tested and said five 
of them had unacceptably high levels 
the report came on the same day an industry group the processed 
apple institute said in washington dc that it tested 4623 
samples of juice and apple sauce and found only eight with 
detectable levels 
consumers union which published consumer reports said 
virtually all the juices containing alar came from processors who 
had pledged not to use alartreated apples it also found the 
chemical in 11 of 20 raw apples purchased in the new york city area 
the government has estimated that only 5 percent to 10 percent 
of apples are sprayed with alar the trade name for daminozide it 
is used to help keep apples on the tree until they are ripe and 
keep them firm and red after harvest 
the chemical got attention recently when a private environmental 
group released a report saying children were at increased risk of 
cancer from eating apples and apple products containing alar 
several cities including new york and los angeles banned 
apples from school cafeterias some later resumed serving apples 
the epa announced last month that it will soon propose a ban on 
daminozide which would probably take effect in late 1990 
at question is what level of the chemical is acceptable the 
federal environmental protection agencys limit is 20 parts per 
million 
the five juices declared unacceptable in the may issue of 
consumer reports had levels ranging from 062 parts per million to 
180 parts per million the industry group said a detectable level 
meant a trace of at least 1 part per million or 20 times below the 
epa limit 
consumers union tested 44 adult apple juices bought in 1988 and 
1989 as well as seven babyfood apple juices 
the brand rated unacceptable by cu and their alar concentrations 
were hudson pride 180 ppm waldbaums 108 pathmark 072 
and pathmark natural style 091 all from the new york region 
and lady lee 062 sold in lucky stores in the west 
all five were rated unacceptable by the magazine not because 
drinking them is likely to cause cancer but because many other 
products are far less likely to contain high alar levels 
responding to cus report the processed apple institute said 
we are pleased that their results so closely mirror our own 
spokesmen for waldbaums and pathmark said they had taken the 
products in question off the shelves they said the stores had been 
assured through legal documents that suppliers didnt use products 
made from alartreated apples 
robert wunderle spokesman for supermarkets general corp 
parent company of pathmark said the company had required apple 
juice suppliers since 1986 to certify they werent made from 
alartreated apples 
are we splitting hairs here or are we dealing with something 
of substance he said of consumer reports cutoff level for 
deeming a product unacceptable 
we have been doing spot testing so this came as a surprise to 
us said mike rourke spokesman for aampp the parent company of 
waldbaums he said the batch tested by consumers union had been 
traced and taken off shelves 
dr edward groth iii associate technical director at consumers 
union said our results show that the industrys voluntary 
boycott of alar isnt working 
consumers union said it found six brands with very low or 
undetectable levels for both years martinellis gold medal minute 
maid musselmans red cheek speas farm and motts natural style 
another seven tested in 1989 showed similarly low levels 
consumers union said key food lincoln lincoln natural style 
lucky leaf veryfine 100 mcintosh finast and a generic brand 
bought at a finast store 
the babyfood apple juices had very low levels cu said with 
beechnut and gerber products having no detectable residues 
</TEXT>
