<TEXT>
venezuelan president carlos andres perez said 
wednesday that us treasury secretary nicholas bradys new plan to 
tackle latin americas debt crisis offers hope for the regions 
troubled democracies 
perez said the brady plan dovetails with proposals developed by 
latin american finance ministers and that together the two plans 
provide an excellent basis for dialogue and a meeting of minds 
perez who spoke in spanish through an interpreter made his 
comments on the first day of the hemispheric agenda a twoday 
conference at the carter center cochaired by former presidents 
jimmy carter and gerald ford 
us secretary of state james baker argentine president raul 
alfonsin uruguayan president julio sanguinetti and other us and 
foreign officials are scheduled to speak thursday 
the conference is aimed at coming up with ideas on key 
hemispheric issues particularly the debt problem 
perez said the latin american democracies 400 billion debt 
places unsustainable pressures on local economies 
he said both the brady and finance ministers plans involve a 
reduction in the amount of the debt extended repayment periods and 
an increase in the capital flows needed to help financially 
strapped countries get on the road to recovery 
recent public disturbances in venezuela illustrate the urgency 
of the change in the debt repayment plan he said 
while the governments of latin america have proven their 
willingness to adopt disciplined administration to prevent 
funds being misused perez said the creditor countries must 
acknowledge latin americas need for a continuing influx of 
investment capital 
under the current debt structure perez said we are being 
drained of our resources by having to make debt payments with the 
meager funds of austerity policies that irremediably affect our 
peoples behavior to the dramatic extent shown recently in 
venezuela 
at least 247 people were killed and scores injured during riots 
two weeks ago in caracas following an austerity program that 
brought steep increases in bus fares gasoline and other goods and 
services 
the unsustainable pressures of the economic crisis on our 
democracies decapitalize all our countries slash our per 
capita income and drastically wipe out the investment necessary to 
restore economic growth perez said 
the venezuelan president said solving chronic economic problems 
is critical for the survival of the latin american democracies 
time is running out for latin america the debt is already 
eroding our democracies assets perez said the solution lies 
in making traditional markets dynamic again but as long as latin 
america is in a state of economic gloom this option will be 
nonexistent 
</TEXT>
