<TEXT>
when members of the albany recorder ensemble 
get together saturday they will be playing a centuriesold song on 
their ancient flutelike instruments in unison with musicians 
around the world 
recorder players from argentina to australia are being asked to 
synchronize their watches and play an old english dance tune the 
night watch to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the american 
recorder society in the eastern time zone the downbeat will come 
at 5 pm saturday 
the old saying that theres strength in numbers will be 
felt tim king director of the sevenmember albany group said 
wednesday this will give us an opportunity to share with people 
all over the world in a common event 
the recorder has a whistle mouthpiece a thumb hole and seven 
finger holes and has a soft reedy tone invented during the 
middle ages they have remained virtually unchanged for hundreds of 
years and were particularly popular during the 16th and 17th 
centuries 
modern flutes overtook the recorder in the 18th century but 
since the 1920s there has been a revival of interest and the 
american recorder society now 4200 has members worldwide 
andy green the societys administrative director said 
recorders are popular because they dont take a lot of skill to 
produce pleasing music 
it means that people who are involved in other things for the 
major part of their lives can still make music and in some cases 
even play great music he said in a telephone interview from the 
groups new york headquarters 
green said its hard to predict how many will take part in the 
playin but judging from preliminary reports they will number in 
the thousands most of them amateurs 
when the time comes saturday ars president martha bixler a 
nationally known recorder performer will give the downbeat for 
hundreds of players assembled in new yorks symphony space theater 
the society has taken pains to see to it that recorder players 
elsewhere whether in groups or in their homes will be playing 
along in unison or as close to it as possible 
along with copies of the night watch the society has mailed 
instructions including starting times in various time zones late 
evening in europe sunday morning in the far east and urging 
participants to be sure to sychronize your watch to the second 
with the radio or the time telephone number they also give a 
suggested metronome tempo 
green called the mass playin saturday a celebration not only 
of the recorder society but of amateur musicians playing 
together and the importance of this in our lives 
john curtis a college professor in valdosta who directs the 
16member valdosta recorder society said the low cost of recorders 
adds to their popularity good plastic instruments sell for about 
20 though the finest wooden recorders can cost hundreds of 
dollars 
its a sort of personal hobby thing said curtis a college 
professor every month we discover one or two more folks who 
like to play 
