<TEXT>
a judge on thursday ordered a 17yearold 
prisoner sent back to alabama to face a murder charge and possible 
death sentence rejecting claims that the move could violate this 
citys ban on capital punishment 
superior court judge stephen f eilperin said turning down 
alabamas extradition request would make the district of columbia 
ban into national policy and turn the district into a haven for 
persons wanted by other states on capital charges 
the judge gave alabama authorities until may 1 to pick up the 
defendant identified only by the initials om he and an uncle are 
charged with murder and arson in the may 1988 firebombing of a 
gasden ala apartment tamel jackson 18 months died in the 
incident 
eilperin postponed the effective date of his order until tuesday 
to give defense attorneys time to appeal he rejected their bid for 
a 30day stay 
the judge said he could find no legal basis for allowing states 
to reject extradition requests they view as morally offensive 
including ones that could subject defendants to capital punishment 
even if such discretion existed he said alabama could get 
around it by certifying om for trial as an adult since the 
supreme court has ruled clearly that states have no such power in 
handling adult extradition requests 
a decision by the alabama courts to treat om as an adult 
could be returned in his absence and would be binding on this 
court eilperin said 
eilperin said the district cannot interpose its objection to 
capital punishment between om and alabama 
alabama is entitled to have alabama law govern criminal acts 
committed on alabama soil by citizens of alabama against citizens 
of alabama he said 
the supreme court is expected to rule in july whether imposing 
the death penalty on defendants who committed murder before age 18 
violates the constitutional prohibition against cruel and unusual 
punishment 
oms lawyers also had contended that the defendant who is 
black cannot receive a fair trial from white etowah county ala 
authorities they cited the death of his father in 1978 and his 
uncle in 1984 both while in the custody of local authorities 
eilperin acknowledged that testimony from the youth his 
grandmother and his friends in gadsden had depicted a dismal 
climate of summary execution illegal jailings and harassment 
but he said the law requires that fair trial claims be raised in 
alabama not the district 
courts do not sit to make moral judgments loosed from law 
he said and while legislative bodies may act on their moral 
perceptions there are limits to their powers especially local 
bodies such as the districts city council 
nothing in the constitution or elsewhere grants the district 
of columbia the power to enforce beyond its borders the districts 
moral opposition to the death penalty he said 
om was arrested by district authorities in december and has 
been fighting extradition ever since 
