<TEXT>
the navy finally resolving a fouryear 
dispute involving what it described as a matter of high national 
security has authorized the commerce department to begin 
publishing detailed maps of the ocean floors surrounding the united 
states 
the decision announced thursday means that most of the 
detailed oceanbottom maps of the socalled exclusive economic zone 
produced by the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
will soon be declassified and released to the public the navy said 
the only maps the navy said it will continue to insist remain 
classified secret are those covering egress routes used by 
ballistic missile submarines sailing from their home ports 
there are four such home ports on the east and west coasts of 
the united states for nuclear missile submarines groton conn 
charleston sc kings bay ga and bangor wash 
the threat assessment and decisionmaking for this issue have 
been a long difficult task rear adm rf pittenger wrote in a 
letter last month to the commerce department noaas parent agency 
of particular interest to you the navy now interposes no 
objection to unclassified release of most of the noaa 
highresolution bathymetry data which is controlled under the white 
housenational security advisor memorandum of jan 7 1985 
all present and future noaa data from the us exclusive 
economic zone may be released except in broad areas to be defined 
around ssbn missile submarine egress routes 
pittenger the oceanographer of the navy sent his letter to 
commerce under secretary dr william e evans on march 23 the navy 
released copies on thursday 
the dispute now being resolved involves an effort by noaa and 
various universities to use a new extremely sophisticated sea 
beam sonar mapping system to produce incredibly detailed maps 
almost like blackandwhite photos of the ocean bottom 
noaa is trying to survey the entire exclusive economic zone 
which runs from 12 miles to 200 miles off the us coast within 
that zone the united states asserts control when it comes to such 
economic development activities as fishing mining and oil drilling 
the noaa maps are likely to prove invaluable to the oil and gas 
industry and companies that lay cables on the sea floor fisherman 
could use them to locate areas where fish congregate and 
eventually the maps could help companies mine strategic minerals 
the navy however saw another danger detailed maps of the 
ocean bottom along americas coast would be particularly useful to 
commanders of soviet submarines both those trying to hunt or 
attack american subs as well as those trying to fix their 
position to launch a missile attack 
in january 1985 the issue came to a head with the white house 
giving the navy the authority to block noaas publication of 
oceanbottom maps 
ever since noaa has been collecting the map data with the sonar 
system but holding back its release at the navys insistence 
noaa has surveyed much of the eez and the data has been 
classified secret the navy said thursday most of the data 
can soon be declassified and maps can be produced for public 
release under this decision 
stan eames a spokesman for noaa declined immediate comment 
thursday on the navys announcement but navy officials said they 
understood that noaa executives were pleased with the decision 
as part of the ruling the navy did decide thursday the sonar 
technology used to produce the maps would continue to be listed on 
the pentagons munitions list meaning it is subject to export 
controls 
this will allow us exports only to countries that will 
guarantee no reexport to east bloc nations the navy said 
