<TEXT>
for the first time since its savannah river 
nuclear weapons plant was built in 1950 the energy department is 
offering performance bonuses and a guaranteed base fee to the 
plants operator department officials said thursday 
william kaspar manager of the departments field office at 
savannah river near aiken sc outlined the payment plan to a 
group of experts advising energy secretary james d watkins on 
safety issues involving the departments nuclear weapons 
facilities which includes 16 major sites in 12 states 
the payment plan which takes effect saturday with the debut of 
a new contractor at savannah river marks a significant departure 
from past practice in which ei du pont de nemours amp co operated 
the plant for 38 years without any fees 
kaspar said the new plan is intended to give du ponts successor 
at savannah river westinghouse electric corp a financial 
incentive to improve operation of the plants three nuclear 
reactors which make materials for nuclear warheads the site also 
includes other facilities that support the nuclear weapons program 
the three reactors have been shut down since last spring because 
of safety concerns last week westinghouse submitted 
recommendations on how to get them running again and their success 
or failure will largely determine how much they earn on the job 
although westinghouses contract is for five years the payment 
plan can be changed each six months kaspar said for the first 
sixmonth period westinghouse can earn a maximum of about 7 
million in performance awards and a minimum of zero he said 
mark silverman an energy department official at savannah river 
who helped draft the payment plan said in an interview that 
westinghouse would be guaranteed a fee of 750000 for running a 
naval fuel fabrication plant at the site plus 125 million for 
managing the rest of the 300squaremile complex 
the performance awards would be in addition to the guaranteed 
fees silverman said the amounts to be offered for subsequent 
sixmonth periods havent been set he said 
kaspar said the departments decisions on granting performance 
bonuses would be based on a detailed list of tasks and standards 
that place the highest priority on safety and quality of 
operations this term was chosen he said to give equal weight 
to production performance and safety achievements 
the energy department and du pont have been heavily criticized 
for putting too much emphasis on meeting production goals at the 
expense of safety concerns 
members of the departments safety advisory group questioned 
kaspar about the strong focus on rewarding excellence saying this 
approach might lead westinghouse to figure it can spend unlimited 
amounts so long as the results are judged to be outstanding the 
companys expenses will be paid in full by the government 
right now im not worrying about overkill on striving for 
excellence kaspar said 
