president bush said thursday that the oil 
spill off alaskas coast is a major tragedy but his 
administration ruled out a federal takeover of the cleanup the 
coast guard chief said the oil tankers path was so wide that a 
child could have navigated it safely 
meanwhile top administration officials reported that the 
cleanup was marred by the shipping companys failure to respond 
swiftly in the hours just after the tanker exxon valdez ran aground 
last friday 
approximately 10 million gallons of crude oil went into the 
water and most of that went into the water in the first five 
hours said transportation secretary samuel k skinner 
he said faster action by the exxon shipping co which owned the 
supertanker might have diminished it the damage somewhat 
while us officials were generally generous in their praise of 
exxons subsequent performance in the cleanup effort adm paul 
yost the coast guard commandant voiced incredulity that the 
accident could have happened at all 
yost said that the largeship channel leading from valdez 
alaska where the tanker had taken on its cargo of crude oil to 
the open gulf of alaska was wide and wellmarked 
weve got 10 miles of open water there and for that vessel to 
come over and hit a reef is almost unbelievable yost told 
reporters 
this is not treacherous in the area they went aground its 10 
miles wide your children could drive a tanker up through it 
obviously something went very badly wrong he said 
he said allegations of alcohol use by the tankers captain 
joseph hazelwood were being closely scrutinized by the government 
at the time the tanker ran aground hazelwood was in his cabin 
and a relatively junior officer third mate gregory cousins was at 
the helm 
yost skinner and environmental protection agency administrator 
william reilly spoke to reporters at the white house after briefing 
bush on their twoday survey of efforts to battle the spreading oil 
slick in alaskas prince william sound 
bush speaking to the association of community and junior 
colleges said the spill the worst in the nations history was 
a subject of concern to all americans today 
departing from his prepared text bush said theres no doubt 
this is a major tragedy both for the environment and for the 
people up there 
he expressed confidence that those involved in the cleanup were 
doing their best to see that the damage is restricted 
but the president said lets be frank there are some very 
serious problems up there right now 
he said the cleanup will not be easy 
at the same time the administration decided against one option 
initially mentioned by bush as a possibility a federal takeover 
of the cleanup process 
skinner said the cleanup operation now appears to be 
wellcoordinated among exxon federal and state agencies and at 
this point there is not a need to federalize this effort 
such a decision might be counterproductive because of the 
coordination that is now going on he added 
reilly said damage to fish and wildlife may be felt there for 
some time to come 
this is obviously a disaster of enormous potential magnitude 
and impact on the environment reilly said it seems inevitable 
that there will be a very substanial impacts 
reilly said bush had given top priority to a federal 
assessment of how to best protect the oildamaged areas of the 
oncepristine area in southern alaska 
reilly said the spill would not change the administrations 
support for oil exploration in the arctic national wildlife refuge 
in northeast alaska 
all things considered it is inconceivable that any nation 
would walk away from the resources that may exist in the magnitude 
that is potentially there in alaska reilly said 
until last friday night the record was pretty good for 
transporting oil through prince william sound the epa chief said 
the three officials will continue to monitor the situation and 
report to the president in 30 days with recommendations including 
possible options for longrange steps said white house press 
secretary marlin fitzwater 
skinner said that at the appropriate time the government 
would decide what penalties are appropriate noting that a 
state criminal investigation was also taking place 
he said he and the other bush officials who toured the disaster 
site had stressed in a meeting with exxon shipping co president 
frank iarossi and other exxon officials our concern that the 
people most affected by this be adequately compensated 
skinner said the exxon officials vowed to put their money 
where their mouth is and that the united states would hold the 
company to its commitment 
the transportation secretary said the supertanker ripped into 
the reef at about 15 knots or about 17 miles per hour 
