a political leader in namibia predicted 
thursday that independence from south africa will not bring the 
dramatic changes many people expect 
the official transition begins saturday along with a ceasefire 
in the 23yearold guerrilla war begins an informal truce has been 
observed for months but south africa and the rebel southwest 
africa peoples organization formally made the formal agreement 
thursday 
martti ahtisaari the un representative who will oversee the 
transition to independence is to arrive friday 
many black namibians believe the united nations will take over 
the territory saturday discrimination will end and south african 
officials will leave 
louis pienaar appointed by south africa to impartially govern 
the territory and run elections said the only immediate change 
will be the presence of mr ahtisaari 
dirk mudge president of a multiracial coalition expected to be 
swapos main competition in the november elections said 
irresponsible people are going around telling namibians that on 
the first of april things will change in this country 
theres going to be a lot of disappointment said mudge 
leader of the democratic turnhalle alliance 
danny tjongarero acting chairman of swapo which has waged 
political and guerrila campaigns for independence since 1966 said 
ahtisaaris arrival is indeed a historic event and one all 
namibians have been looking forward to 
our people in the townships see the arrival of the united 
nations as assuming responsibility over namibia tjongarero said 
pienaar said he will not rescind laws providing for racially 
segregated schools hospitals and municipal governments but after 
consultation with ahtisaari will begin repealing discriminatory 
laws that may hinder a free and fair election 
he said his first proclamation effective next week will remove 
all obstacles to political meetings previously restricted by 
security legislation south africa has administered namibia since 
world war i and the united nations has been trying to get it out of 
the territory since 1966 the south africans agreed to the 
independence plan as part of a regional accord that also calls for 
withdrawal of cuban troops from angola 
rf botha the south african foreign minister said prime 
minister margaret thatcher of britain is expected in namibia this 
weekend as the transition to independence begins 
he said mrs thatcher probably would visit british members of 
the un peacekeeping force that will monitor elections scheduled 
for november 
the un group will consist of 4650 un peacekeepers 500 
police monitors 620 election monitors from various nations at 
least 760 un civilian administrators and 820 locally hired staff 
the south african government said thursday no territory or 
colony in africa had been as well prepared for independence as 
namibia and gave itself the credit 
it said south africa had provided more resources to namibia 
than any colonial power devoted to the development of territories 
under its control 
