<TEXT>
a decline in marriage doesnt mean young people 
are avoiding having a continuing relationship population analysts 
said thursday adding that living together is replacing matrimony 
for some pairs at least for a while 
both in behavior and attitude the timing of the marriage 
ceremony is becoming a matter of personal taste and convenience and 
less a major lifecourse transition said larry bumpass of the 
university of wisconsin 
bumpass told a session of the population association of america 
that between half and twothirds of the decline in marriage among 
young people can be accounted for by a rise in cohabitation 
for example he said among people under age 20 the share 
married declined from 27 percent in 1970 to 14 percent in 1985 but 
the figure for people involved in a union including marriage and 
cohabitation slipped only from 29 percent to 23 percent 
for people aged 25 or over bumpass said the marriage drop was 
from 72 percent to 55 percent over the same years but including 
those living together meant people in a union declined from 75 
percent to 69 percent 
federal statistics on cohabiting adults are weak statisticians 
have said because they also include people rooming together and 
other situations in which the people are not having an intimate 
relationship bumpass based his report on the national survey of 
families and households an indepth analysis of 13017 households 
he disputed a popular notion that people cohabiting are 
welleducated affluent young persons 
rather bumpass and other analysts reported people living 
together were more likely to have lower incomes and less education 
than others 
linda a jacobsen of cornell university suggested that financial 
problems may lead to a decision to cohabit in many cases with 
young people unable to afford to set up housekeeping on their own 
they often face a need to trade privacy for companionship and 
household economies she said 
a decline in marriage among younger people doesnt mean they 
have abandoned the institution said odalia ho wong of the 
university of marylandbaltimore 
women are postponing marriage and families to complete their 
education and launch a career she said but eventually most do wed 
and are then in a financial condition to consider children soon 
after marriage rather than waiting 
christine a bachrach of the center for population research 
agreed that economics likely plays an important part in 
cohabitation but she said that population experts may be giving 
too little attention to another important factor sex 
marriage ages were unusually low in the decades following world 
war ii while early in this century weddings were delayed as they 
are now with financial considerations a factor she said 
but cohabitation was not as common years ago as it has become 
she added and this increase must be considered to be a part of a 
sexual revolution something more tolerated now 
in addition to economics the population experts said other 
factors that are important include a desire to screen a potential 
marriage partner 
