<TEXT>
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev cut 
an expensive deal with the kgb to defeat a serious challenge to his 
political reforms a private kremlinologist says in a study being 
released friday 
the september 1988 bargain placed kgb chief viktor chebrikov in 
a position to influence constitutional revisions and possibly 
become a candidate for supreme power himself said researcher 
jeremy azrael a former state department policy planner 
azrael said chebrikov is believed to be uneasy with the pace of 
reform in the country 
gorbachev is in an uphill battle azrael wrote in a summary 
of the study he won a very narrow victory based on cutting a 
deal with the head of the kgb who is on record as being dubious 
about his policies chebrikov is not only the chief contender 
should gorbachev go bellyup but someone who is evidently willing 
to give him a shove in that direction 
azraels analysis comes in a study by the rand corp a 
governmentsupported think tank the 137000 study was done for 
the governmentfunded national council for soviet and east european 
research and the center for the study of soviet international 
behavior a joint operation of rand and the university of 
california at los angeles 
the study doesnt address the implications of the soviet unions 
weekend elections for a new national congress the most competitive 
elections there since 1917 embarrassing defeats for many communist 
party regulars raised the possibility of a backlash against 
gorbachevs reforms 
gorbachev may have headed off a bloodless coup of the kind that 
deposed nikita s khrushchev in 1964 through the intercession of 
the kgb the soviet secret police and intelligence agency at a 
september 1988 plenum of the partys central committee azrael 
writes 
however the researcher suggests that a humiliating defeat of 
his political reforms rather than his ouster was the more likely 
intent of a group of gorbachev adversaries that included his chief 
rival yegor ligachev 
it was only after chebrikov made it clear that the kgb was 
firmly on gorbachevs side and was prepared to play political 
hardball on his behalf that gorbachevs opponents relented the 
study says 
ligachev was demoted from his no 2 position in the party and 
several other gorbachev opponents on the politburo were retired 
after the meeting 
in contrast kgb chief chebrikov was made secretary of the 
partys central committee and his allies were installed to head 
the committee on party control and the kgb itself 
azrael disagreed with those who believe that the political power 
of the kgb has waned in recent years 
before the pivotal september 1988 central committee plenum 
azrael writes chebrikov undermined gorbachevs liberalization 
programs by engineering the ouster of prominent gorbachev ally 
boris yeltsin from party leadership 
there also is evidence the kgb encouraged ethnic violence in the 
soviet republics of armenia and azerbaijan in the spring and summer 
of 1988 to demonstrate the dangers of rapid political 
liberalization azrael wrote 
