<TEXT>
people knew paulino fernandez as a 
reserved distant man obsessed with his plots of land in this 
isolated mountain hamlet but one day the 64yearold farmer 
unsheathed the knife he used to slaughter pigs and stabbed six 
neighbors to death 
then he burned himself to death in his farmhouse 
news of the killings march 7 caught the attention of all spain 
it had happened in galicia a longignored underdeveloped 
northwestern region where only 27 percent of the population lives 
in cities 
it appears clearly to have been an attack of madness said 
historian ramon villares paz yet its a paradigmatic incident a 
sort of death cry of a rural society of elderly people with a 
tightly held conviction that their culture has no future 
surribas is isolated like a majority of villages in galicia 
populated mainly by old people with problems of communication 
between them without any future without horizons 
galicia is sometimes called spains ireland because of its 
celtic origins the playing of bagpipes is common and every summer 
an international celtic music festival is held in ortigueira 
attracting musicians from all the celtic regions of europe the 
celtic cross is a familiar sight throughout galicia and a dance 
called the muneira is similar to the irish jig 
galicia is a fourprovince region of verdant hilly land 
geographically cut off from the rest of the country by poor 
communications and a rugged mountain range ringing its eastern 
flank and its southern border with portugal 
since prehistoric times it has been characterized by a social 
and economic structure not usual in the rest of spain 
subsistence farming remains the norm in much of the interior of 
galicia today 
and there lived paulino fernandez in his farmhouse with his 
fears 
paulino had been extremely worried about someone taking his 
land but he faced no threat of any kind and had normal relations 
with neighbors said sergio vazquez yebra fernandezs lawyer and 
mayor of the nearby town of chantada 
the galician village is a world subject to drastic 
transformations wrote columnist carlos luis rodriguez in la voz 
de galicia the regions leading newspaper 
the crime is in part an expression of the daily dramas of 
rural galicia that stun us because they shatter our ideal of the 
bucolic village 
the galician village is a genuine pressure cooker where all 
kinds of conflicts simmer over a low fire and where the modern and 
the ancestral crash into each other as if upon a breakwater 
the peasant who listens to the sermon of the parish priest in 
the morning and watches dallas on television by the light of the 
hearth must necessarily suffer a shock due to the sudden clash 
between a world view proper of the last century with another that 
is an advance of that to come in the next century between 1950 
and 1970 the region of 3 million people underwent a rapid but 
incomplete industrialization mainly involving shipbuilding and 
steel plants on the atlantic coast 
but more than 20000 relatively recent highpaying jobs were 
lost in these smokestack industries through drastic restructuring 
forced by spains decadelong economic recession that ended in 1984 
galicia contributes less than 6 percent to spains gross 
national product and agriculture still dominates the economy 
potatoes corn grapes and cabbage are the principal crops and 
the dairy industry provides 25 percent of the milk for spains 39 
million people 
paulino fernandezs obsession with his land rang true to the 
galicians fabled ties to the earth and their legendary longing for 
it after they had emigrated to latin america or more recently to 
west germany or france 
an estimated 1 million galicians haunted by the specter of a 
dark future left in this century 
among the bestknown products of galicia are cubas fidel castro 
and raul alfonsin the president of argentina 
other spaniards see galicians or gallegos as melancholy 
broodingly pessimistic people obsessed with death and witchcraft 
they are also known for their cunning and their contradictory 
nature 
if you see a gallego on a staircase a popular saying goes 
you can never tell if hes going up or coming down 
while galicians sometimes exaggerate their love for their 
homeland in many cases when they move to other parts of the 
country they identify themselves more with spain than with galicia 
and have a lovehate relationship with their birthplace said 
mayuor vazquez yebra 
the historian villares paz said paulino fernandezs violent 
attack on his unsuspecting neighbors was more than homicide an 
incident that suggests a kind of attempt at collective 
selfpunishment we have no exit where can we go we have no 
future 
</TEXT>
