<TEXT>
when workers at the savannah river plant 
report for duty monday theyll find a new name on the entrance sign 
and a new logo on their coffee cups small symbols of broad change 
at the nations largest nuclear weapons plant 
after 38 years of operating the sprawling weapons plant for the 
energy department chemical giant ei du pont de nemours amp co is 
giving way to westinghouse electric co leaving behind a backlog 
of problems that some say jeopardize national security 
the three active nuclear reactors at savannah river plant have 
been shut down for nearly a year because of safety and structural 
problems and a series of mishaps in recent months has raised 
doubts about whether improvements are likely anytime soon the 
reactors are the nations only source of tritium a highly 
radioactive gas used at other government defense plants to make 
nuclear warheads 
the pentagon has said that unless at least one of the reactors 
is restarted by the end of this year it might have to deactivate 
some warheads to preserve supplies 
the energy department is beleaguered by safety and operational 
problems throughout its nuclear weapons complex which includes 16 
major plants in 12 states savannah river has been the focus of 
criticism because it forms the most vital link in the chain of 
nuclear weapons development production and testing 
as a result the departments massive effort to rejuvenate 
savannah river has become a testing ground for its controversial 
plan to spend at least 81 billion over the next two decades to 
modernize and clean up the weapons complex 
westinghouse has vowed to impose a stricter more streamlined 
brand of management and a new approach to ensuring reactor safety 
westinghouse officially took over as the energy departments 
contractor on saturday although for most of the roughly 20000 
people who work at the site in western south carolina monday will 
provide the first taste of life with a new boss 
some of the immediate changes are symbolic such as changing the 
name to savannah river site to reflect the idea that its 
laboratories and other support facilties are crucial to the safe 
operation of its beleaguered nuclear reactors 
some outside experts question how effective westinghouses 
changes will be and even the companys top managers concede some 
improvements may be slow in coming 
were going to have problems believe me said james moore 
president of westinghouse savannah river co a unit of the 
pittsburghbased parent company i hope what people will find is 
different is that when we have those problems therell be a 
different way of solving them 
john ahearne chairman of an energy department advisory group 
said in a recent interview that westinghouse may find it difficult 
to impose change throughout the huge workforce since it has 
brought in only a small number of its own managers westinghouse 
has kept on more than 97 percent of the du pont staff 
moore said he wanted a large share of the du pont people to stay 
to provide continuity 
du pont has defended its record at savannah river saying it 
fulfilled its mission of helping build and maintain the nations 
nuclear arsenal it has stressed that no one ever was injured as a 
result of any accidents at the plant 
moore is reluctant to criticize du ponts performance although 
he suggested in an interview with the associated press that du pont 
was out of its depth 
du ponts a good company but theyre a chemical company 
moore said in his transition office a few miles from the plant 
theyre not a nuclear company and they really dont have any way 
of getting any specific interaction with the commercial side of 
the business weve been steeped in it from day one 
westinghouse is the worlds largest builder of commercial 
nuclear power plants it also is the energy departments contractor 
at nuclear weapons plants in washington state and ohio 
taking over operation of the savannah river plant is a massive 
undertaking for westinghouse 
besides the plants three active nuclear reactors code named 
k l and p reactors two others are permanently shut down the 
site also includes a research laboratory a chemical separations 
plant that makes weapongrade plutonium a facility that fabricates 
fuel for the navys nuclear fleet and a plant that makes fuel to 
run the onsite nuclear reactors a building that prepares 
highlevel nuclear waste for permanent disposal is due to open 
later this year 
the emphasis on safety and secrecy at savannah river is obvious 
from a tour of the 300squaremile site 
armed guards in combat fatigues patrol the area which is closed 
to the public slogans are posted on large signposts near buildings 
and among the ramrodstraight loblolly pines that cover much of the 
site mums the word says one others say security protects 
your jobs and take safety home 
moore and other officials interviewed at savannah river said 
recent national publicity about the reactor problems has unfairly 
cast the plants workers in a bad light 
theyve really been dumped on said moore he praised the 
workers dedication and said the main problem has been inadequate 
training for reactor operators whose decisions in the event of a 
reactor mishap are critical to avoiding a catastrophy 
were not going to make nuclear physicists out of all the 
operators but were going to give them a better understanding of 
whats behind some of the procedures moore said 
andrew cwalina a member of the management team preparing for 
restart of the k reactor and a 15year savannah river plant 
veteran said most workers are receptive to westinghouses ideas 
for change 
some view it as a matter of survival he said 
the energy department too is changing its ways it has decided 
that the amount of money to be paid to westinghouse under its 
fiveyear contract will depend on how well it performs in the 
first six months of the contract westinghouse could earn a maximum 
of 75 million or it could get nothing said mark silverman a 
department official at savannah river who helped write the award 
fee plan 
du pont at its own insistence received no fees for operating 
the plant although all its expenses were covered by the 
government as is the case with westinghouse 
one could argue there was relatively little incentive for du 
pont even to do all that doe asked of them said silverman let 
alone strive for improvement 
