<TEXT>
here is a brief rundown of the governments more 
than 2yearold investigation of the investment firm drexel burnham 
lambert inc and its highyield bond financier michael r milken 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the nations fifthlargest securities firm last december agreed 
to plead guilty to six felony counts for securities and mail fraud 
and pay a record 650 million in fines and restitution 
the charges brought by the us attorneys office in manhattan 
included stock manipulation fraudulent filings with the securities 
and exchange commission and a stock parking scheme with 
nowimprisoned inside trader ivan boesky 
drexel said it agreed to the deal with the government rather 
than face a racketeering indictment that could have frozen its 
assets and crippled its operations 
under the deal drexel agreed to fire michael milken and 
withhold his 1988 compensation estimated at between 100 million 
and 200 million it agreed to similar terms for milkens brother 
lowell a drexel executive 
the milkens and former drexel trader bruce lee newberg were 
charged wednesday in a 98count racketeering and securities fraud 
indictment handed up by a federal grand jury 
drexel will not formally plead guilty under the criminal plea 
bargain until the firm settles civil charges with the sec and a 
federal judge approves the deals 
the government began investigating drexel and milken in late 
1986 after the firm was named by boesky who agreed to pay 100 
million and cooperate with the government to settle insider trading 
charges against him 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the sec last september accused drexel milken and five others of 
fraudulent schemes including insider trading stock manipulation 
failure to disclose stock ownership and other violations of 
securities laws the civil complaint says milken schemed with 
boesky in at least 16 transactions that violated securities laws 
negotiations between drexel and the sec hit numerous roadblocks 
and stalled earlier this month when the government demanded the 
firm fire milken before the settlement was completed one proposed 
condition would bans milken from the firm for life and bars other 
drexel employees from talking business with him 
the sec deal is a precondition for settlement of criminal 
charges against the firm 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milken has denied all allegations against him he has been a 
focus of government investigators for more than two years 
the 42yearold junk bond financier received a letter from the 
government last fall indicating he would be indicted on charges 
including racketeering and securities fraud 
milken is challenging drexels criminal settlement in federal 
court charging it violates his constitutional rights by forcing 
the firm to fire him and withhold his 1988 pay an april hearing is 
scheduled the case is not expected to derail the plea agreement 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0205 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
financier michael milken accused 
racketeer also has been called a devoted father a generous 
supporter of charity and creator of the most innovative financial 
engine of the century 
milken 42 head of drexel burnham lambert incs highyield 
bond division was indicted wednesday by a manhattan federal grand 
jury for massive securities law and racketeering violations in the 
ivan boesky insidertrading probe 
while the indictment apparently will cost the trader his job and 
compensation of more than 100 million a year the muchpublicized 
investigation has done little to dim milkens image in the eyes of 
friends and those who have profited from the junkbond market he 
created 
as recently as january barbara firestone who runs a los 
angeles organization for retarded or emotionally disturbed 
children sang the praises of a man who has donated hundreds of 
thousands of dollars and given unstintingly of his time 
its not the man you see in the newspaper ms firestone 
said of milken 
through three family foundations milken and his brother 
lowell gave more than 17 million to 200 charities over the last 
six years 
milkens place in modern financial history appears assured by 
his role as the virtually singlehanded creator of the modern 
market in junk bonds 
the highrisk highinterest bonds have been used to quickly 
raise large cash war chests for corporate takeover strategists and 
to fund business expansion by those who couldnt persuade banks or 
more conservative venture capitalists to back their efforts 
a dozen years ago milken began preaching the value of the 
bonds which were issued by companies not strong enough to command 
favorable ratings from the agencies that advise investors on the 
soundness of corporate bonds because they are low rated junk 
bonds have to offer higher interest rates to attract investors than 
do bonds with higher ratings 
milken reasoned that by buying a diverse portfolio of junk 
bonds an investor could hedge against the risk of default by any 
one company the explosive growth of the junk bond market 
responsible in part for waves of corporate takeovers in recent 
years is credited to milkens fervant advocacy 
drexel dominated the market largely because of milken who 
presided over an informal network of satisfied clients those who 
had successfully financed a deal by selling junk bonds stood 
willing to buy bonds issued by others 
