<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency today 
added 101 sites in 33 states to its list of hazardous waste dumps 
that pose the greatest longterm threat to public health and the 
environment 
the additions bring to 1163 the number of waste sites eligible 
for federal funds under the epas 85 billion superfund 
cleanup program 
epa identifies and ranks the sites on its list according to 
health threats to nearby populations through contamination of 
groundwater surface water or air money for the cleanup fund comes 
from taxes mainly on the chemical industry 
the latest additions to the superfund list include garbage 
dumps refineries dry cleaners chemical dumps and a variety of 
manufacturing plants including a steel company tanning company 
paint works and a forest products company 
pennsylvania had the most sites 12 followed by new york with 
10 and michigan with seven 
of the total sites identified so far new jerseys 107 is the 
most for any state pennsylvania is second with 94 followed by 
california with 88 the list was started in 1983 
the epa has been under attack for years for the pace of cleanup 
under the superfund program which was created by congress in 
response to a series of dramatic toxic waste problems that surfaced 
in the late 1970s and early 1980s 
various congressional reports criticized the program last year 
resulting in congress cutting the cleanup budget by 175 million 
in a statement accompanying todays announcement that 101 sites 
had been added to the superfund list epa administrator william k 
reilly said he was trying to speed up the process 
the slow progress of superfund frustrates a lot of people i 
know he said it frustrates me at epa were looking at ways 
to speed up this process and to spur cleanups by responsible 
private parties including making expanded use of enforcement 
actions 
the latest additions to the cleanup priority list include eight 
federal facilities although superfund money cannot be used for 
cleanup on federal sites the epa said it had decided to put 
eligible sites on the list regardless of their regulatory status 
federal agencies and the military services are required to pay for 
hazardous waste site cleanups out of their own budgets 
the epa said that in addition to the eight federal sites added 
to the superfund list it has decided to extend the site area of 
the rocky mountain arsenal near denver which already was on the 
list the extension was made to include contaminants and releases 
from an area of the arsenal called basin f the agency said 
