a group of us corporations on thursday signed a wideranging 
agreement with the soviet union setting the framework for new joint 
ventures worth up to 10 billion over 20 years 
the group calling itself the american trade consortium has 
been negotiating for a year to complete the deal with the soviet 
foreign economic consortium which establishes a legal and business 
framework for the development of joint ventures between the groups 
the us consortium consists of giant food processer archer 
daniels midland co chevron corp eastman kodak co personal 
products maker johnson johnson rjr nabisco inc and the 
mercator corp a banking concern 
some of the possible joint ventures that now will be negotiated 
include oilseed processing manufacture of computer discs 
production of crackers cereals tobacco products and sweeteners 
and oil and gas exploration 
but although at least one member of the atc indicated it was 
moving ahead with talks to set up joint ventures several major 
hurdles remain 
additionally one original member of the group ford motor co 
dropped out of the consortium saying there had not been enough 
progress to warrant its continued participation 
a significant issue is the repatriation of profits from the 
soviet union which has been a key obstacle in previous attempts by 
western companies to do business there the soviet ruble is not 
convertible and any profits earned in rubles are worthless outside 
the country 
james h giffen president of the american group said in an 
announcement from moscow that thursdays agreement resolves that 
issue in principle but he declined to provide details 
feasibility studies will be conducted over the next year and 
giffen said the first of some 25 joint ventures could strt up 
within 18 months 
kodak indicated it was negotiating seven joint ventures to 
market cameras film and other photographic products and to process 
photographic film other ventures would sell computer discs and a 
blood analyzer 
