import restrictions on british swine and pork 
products are bring reduced as a result of britains eradication of 
hog cholera the agriculture department said thursday 
the disease which is highly contagious and often fatal to 
swine does not affect humans the united states was declared free 
of hog cholera in 1978 following a 15year eradication program 
swine and uncooked pork products from britain have been banned 
from us entry since april 11 1986 
larry b slagle acting administrator of the departments animal 
and plant health inspection service said hog cholera has not been 
reported in britain since august 1987 
the rule change effective immediately will affect some us 
swine producers who have expressed an interest in obtaining 
breeding stock swine semen or both from britain he said however 
such imports are not expected to have a large impact on us swine 
producers slagle added 
small quantities of untreated pork and pork products from 
britain that are for personal consumption will be allowed to enter 
the united states he said however commercial shipments may 
originate only from pork processing plants that meet us 
requirements 
